  "prompt": "Why the colour of wires in homes are black, green and red?",
  "response": "The color coding of electrical wires in homes is standardized to ensure safety and consistency, making it easier to identify the purpose of each wire. The colors you mentioned\u2014black, green, and red\u2014have specific meanings in electrical wiring:\n\n1. **Black Wire**:  \n   - The black wire is typically used as the **hot wire** or **live wire** in electrical circuits.  \n   - It carries the current from the power source (e.g., the electrical panel) to the load (e.g., a light fixture or outlet).  \n   - In some cases, red or blue wires may also be used as hot wires in more complex circuits.\n\n2. **Green Wire (or Bare Copper Wire)**:  \n   - The green wire (or bare copper wire) is the **ground wire**.  \n   - Its purpose is to provide a safe path for electrical current in the event of a fault, preventing electric shock or fire.  \n   - It is connected to the grounding system and usually does not carry current under normal conditions.\n\n3. **Red Wire**:  \n   - The red wire is often used as a **secondary hot wire** in electrical circuits.  \n   - It is commonly used in 3-way or 4-way switch setups (for controlling lights from multiple locations) or in 240-volt circuits (e.g., for appliances like dryers or stoves).  \n   - In some cases, it can also indicate a switched hot wire.\n\n### Additional Wire Colors:\n- **White or Gray Wire**: These wires are **neutral wires**. They complete the circuit by returning current to the power source.  \n- **Blue or Yellow Wire**: These colors are often used as additional hot wires in more complex circuits, such as in multi-wire branch circuits or for specific appliance connections.\n\n### Why Are Colors Important?\n- **Safety**: Properly identifying wires helps prevent accidental contact with live wires.  \n- **Consistency**: Standardized colors make it easier for electricians and homeowners to understand and troubleshoot wiring systems.  \n- **Compliance**: Following color codes ensures compliance with electrical codes and regulations, which vary slightly by region.\n\nAlways consult local electrical codes and standards, as color conventions may differ slightly depending on the country or region.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
